A '''conceptual space''' is a geometric structure that represents a number of [[Quality (philosophy)|quality]] [[dimension]]s, which denote basic features by which concepts and objects can be compared, such as [[weight]], [[color]], [[taste]], [[temperature]], [[Pitch (music)|pitch]], and the [[Three-dimensional space|three ordinary spatial dimensions]].<ref name="ZenkerGärdenfors2015">{{cite book |editor1-last=Zenker |editor1-first=Frank |editor2-last=Gärdenfors |editor2-first=Peter |editor2-link=Peter Gärdenfors |date=2015 |title=Applications of conceptual spaces: the case for geometric knowledge representation |series=[[Synthese]] library: studies in epistemology, logic, methodology, and philosophy of science |volume=359 |location=Cham |publisher=[[Springer-Verlag]] |isbn=3319150200 |oclc=907771045}}</ref><ref name="Kriegeskorte2013">Kriegeskorte, N., & Kievit, R. A. (2013). Representational geometry: Integrating cognition, computation, and the brain. ''Trends in Cognitive Sciences, 17''(8), 401–412. http://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2013.06.007</ref>{{rp|4}} In a conceptual space, ''points'' denote objects, and ''regions'' denote concepts. The theory of conceptual spaces is a theory about [[concept learning]] first proposed by [[Peter Gärdenfors]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Gärdenfors |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Gärdenfors |title=Conceptual spaces: the geometry of thought |year=2000 |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |isbn=0262071991 |oclc=42389577}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Gärdenfors |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Gärdenfors |date=2014 |title=Geometry of meaning: semantics based on conceptual spaces |location=Cambridge, Massachusetts |publisher=[[MIT Press]] |isbn=9780262026789 |oclc=854541601}}</ref><ref name="Foo2001">Foo, N. (2001). Conceptual Spaces—The Geometry of Thought. ''AI Magazine, 22''(1), 139–140. Retrieved from https://www.aaai.org/ojs/index.php/aimagazine/article/viewPDFInterstitial/1554/1453%5Cnpapers2://publication/uuid/4FC4A7BC-BD5B-4448-8B19-B42DCA4480EE</ref> It is motivated by notions such as conceptual [[Similarity (psychology)|similarity]] and [[prototype theory]].
The theory also puts forward the notion that ''natural'' categories are [[convex set|convex]] regions in conceptual spaces.<ref name="ZenkerGärdenfors2015"/>{{rp|5}} In that if <math>x</math> and <math>y</math> are elements of a category, and if <math>z</math> is between <math>x</math> and <math>y</math>, then <math>z</math> is also likely to belong to the category. The notion of concept convexity allow the interpretation of the focal points of regions as category [[prototype theory|prototypes]]. In the more general formulations of the theory, concepts are defined in terms conceptual similarity to their prototypes.
