'''Doreen Kimura''' (born Doreen Goebel 1933 in [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]] – February 27, 2013) was a Canadian psychologist who was professor at the [[University of Western Ontario]] and professor emeritus at [[Simon Fraser University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.yourlifemoments.ca/sitepages/obituary.asp?oId=688604 |title=Doreen Kimura – Obituaries – London, ON – Your Life Moments |publisher=Yourlifemoments.ca |date= |accessdate=2013-03-14}}</ref> She was the founding president of the [[Society for Academic Freedom and Scholarship]].
==Career== Kimura held a PhD in [[psychobiology]]. Her interests included the relationship between sex and cognition (see [[sex and intelligence]]) and promoting [[academic freedom]].
While some criticized [[Lawrence Summers]]' claims that differences in male-female representation in the sciences could be due to innate ability, Kimura supported him.<ref>[https://www.sfu.ca/~dkimura/articles/hysteria.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050920220223/http://www.sfu.ca/~dkimura/articles/hysteria.htm |date=September 20, 2005 }}</ref> She was a critic of [[affirmative action]], arguing that it is demeaning to women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safs.ca/meritdiversity/kimura1.html |title=kimura1 |publisher=Safs.ca |date= |accessdate=2013-03-14}}</ref> She also supported the concept of the biological origin of differences in cognitive ability between males and females (see also [[nature versus nurture]]).
According to the CISG's (Canadian Inter-Organizational Steering Group for Speech-Language Pathology and Audiology) 'Canadian Guidelines on Auditory Processing Disorder in Children and Adults: Assessment and Intervention' (December 2012), "In 1961, Doreen Kimura proposed a theory that would attempt to explain dichotic listening abilities in humans. As a testament to her theory, her views on dichotic processing of auditory information recently celebrated a 50th anniversary."
==Personal life== Kimura was the mother of Charlotte Thistle, grandmother of Ella Archer, and sister of Shelagh Derouin and Amber Harvey.
==Books== *''Neuromotor mechanisms in human communication'' (1993), Oxford: [[OUP]] {{ISBN|0-19-505492-X}} *''Sex and Cognition'' (2000), Cambridge, MA: [[MIT Press]] {{ISBN|0-262-61164-3}}
